comment.author: 27541657@N07
comment._content: Could that plane be a Culver Cadet?  Or a Moony Mite?

comment.author: 27541657@N07
comment._content: the fuel gauge on the back of the cockpit looks like a Culver Cadet.

comment.author: 70824666@N08
comment._content: It's a very early Mooney Mite with the original converted Crosley auto engine, making it one of 7 sold in 1948, and before they were all recalled for replacement of the Crosley with a Lycoming O-145, a true aircraft engine.

comment.author: 49487266@N07
comment.authorname: San Diego Air & Space Museum Archives

comment.author: 27541657@N07
comment._content:
I agree it is a Mooney Mite, the one we have in our museum has the Lycoming engine 
.  That's what confused me before.  I understand that Mr. Culver helped design the the Mite for the Mooney company.  He left the gas gauge behind the pilot just like the Cadet.
